    bio: 'Baruch Spinoza was born in Amsterdam in 1632, the son of Portuguese Jewish immigrants who had fled the Inquisition to find refuge in the Dutch Republic. Raised in the city\'s vibrant Sephardic Jewish community, he received a thorough education in Hebrew scripture, Talmudic commentary, and the medieval Jewish rationalists, particularly Maimonides. He also immersed himself in the new science of Galileo and Descartes, and this combination of religious tradition and radical rationalism would shape the extraordinary philosophy he was quietly developing. In 1656, when he was just twenty-three, the Amsterdam community issued against him one of the harshest writs of excommunication in its history, for "abominable heresies" that were never precisely specified but clearly included his unorthodox views about God, the immortality of the soul, and the authority of scripture.\n\nAfter his excommunication, Spinoza supported himself as a lens grinder — a trade that placed the very instruments of rational observation in his hands — and pursued philosophy in deliberate, productive seclusion. His masterwork, the Ethics, was written in geometric form, with definitions, axioms, propositions, and demonstrations modeled on Euclid, as if to show that metaphysical truths could be derived with the same rigor as mathematical theorems. The central and scandalous claim of the Ethics is that God and Nature are one and the same infinite substance — Deus sive Natura — a thoroughgoing pantheism that outraged both religious authorities and many secular readers. He also argued that the human mind and body are not two substances (as Descartes had maintained) but two attributes — thought and extension — of a single underlying reality, dissolving the mind-body problem by denying the dualism that had created it.\n\nSpinoza\'s political philosophy was equally radical for his time and place. His Theological-Political Treatise, published anonymously in 1670, argued for freedom of thought and expression, secular governance, and the historical-critical interpretation of the Bible as a human document — ideas that anticipated the Enlightenment by decades and modern biblical scholarship by centuries. He believed democracy was the most natural form of government because it best preserved individual reason and the freedom that is essential to human flourishing. Though he was widely denounced as an atheist in his lifetime and published little under his own name, his influence grew enormously after his death: Hegel declared that to do philosophy one must first be a Spinozist, and his influence can be traced through Romantic nature philosophy, Einstein\'s professed religious outlook, and contemporary philosophy of mind.',
